":"1115","aproximadamente 1190":"omkring 1190","Genova, Liguria, Italie":"Genova, Liguria, Italien","Genova, Liguria, Italia":"Genova, Liguria, Italien"},"nl":{"environ 1140–environ 1190":"circa 1140–circa 1190","1140–1190":"1140–1190","1140–1185":"1140–1185","1160–1190":"1160–1190","1165–1217":"1165–1217","1182–1220":"1182–1220","1115–1170":"1115–1170","1190":"1190","aproximadamente 1160":"circa 1160","aproximadamente 1182":"circa 1182","environ 1185":"circa 1185","environ 1140":"circa 1140","1165":"1165","1220":"1220","1185":"1185","environ 1170":"circa 1170","1140":"1140","environ 1190":"circa 1190","1182":"1182","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1217":"1217","1115":"1115","aproximadamente 1190":"circa 1190","Genova, Liguria, Italie":"Genova, Liguria, Italië","Genova, Liguria, Italia":"Genova, Liguria, Italië"},"en":{"environ 1140–environ 1190":"about 1140–about 1190","1140–1190":"1140–1190","1140–1185":"1140–1185","1160–1190":"1160–1190","1165–1217":"1165–1217","1182–1220":"1182–1220","1115–1170":"1115–1170","1190":"1190","aproximadamente 1160":"about 1160","aproximadamente 1182":"about 1182","environ 1185":"about 1185","environ 1140":"about 1140","1165":"1165","1220":"1220","1185":"1185","environ 1170":"about 1170","1140":"1140","environ 1190":"about 1190","1182":"1182","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1217":"1217","1115":"1115","aproximadamente 1190":"about 1190","Genova, Liguria, Italie":"Genova, Liguria, Italy","Genova, Liguria, Italia":"Genova, Liguria, Italy","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Grimaldi","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Mario, Angelo, Antonio, Giuseppe, Sal, Santo, Aniello, Ascanio, Carmela, Franco, Giovanni, Marco, Marino, Massimo.  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Luis, Carlos.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of the personal name   Grimaldo  . This surname is also found in Corsica and southern France.","History: This is the name of the ruling family of the principality of Monaco. They came to Monaco from Genoa in the 13th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Grimaldo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Jesus, Manuel, Luis, Francisco, Pedro, Gerardo, Jorge, Pablo, Roberto, Rogelio.","Spanish: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>grīm</i> ‘mask, helmet’ + <i>wald</i> ‘rule’. This surname is most common in Mexico."]}]},{"name":"di","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 狄, a term referring to the tribes in ancient northern China: (i) from Di (狄), the name of an ancient state (thought to have been located in Hebei or Shandong province), which was granted to Xiao Bo or Kao Bo by King Cheng of Zhou (reigned 1042–1021  BC ). (ii) adopted as a surname by the Ku Di (庫狄) family during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) traced back to other minority ethnic groups in ancient northwestern China.","Mandarin form of the Chinese surname 邸, meaning ‘official residence’ in Chinese: (i) from placename Di (邸), the name of a county (unidentified location). (ii) said to be borne by some descendants of Kujula Kadphises (called 丘就郤 or 邸就郤 in Chinese, 30–<i>c.</i> 80  AD ), founder of the Kushan Empire (one branch of the Yuezhi people originating from western China) located in Central Asia during the Eastern Han dynasty (25–220  AD )."],"variants":[{"name":"Chi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Dong, Yun, Cheng, Jae, Yong, Cheng Chung, Chi, Chun, Duk, Fang, Feng.  Korean Chung, Chong, Jae Hong, Moon, Myong, Pong, Shen, Yoo, Byung, Chang, Chol, Chong Hun.  Southeast Asian Phi, Hung, Ly, Tu, Denh, Do Van, Duong, Hao, Kieu, Mui, Nga, Phat.","Chinese: Mandarin and Cantonese form of the surname 池, meaning ‘moat’ in ancient Chinese: (i) acquired as a surname by people who lived beside a moat. (ii) from Chi (池), said to be the name of an ancient state (of unknown location and period). (iii) from the personal name Chi (池), personal name of a son of an official in the state of Qin during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","Chinese: Mandarin and Cantonese form of the surname 遲, meaning ‘late’ in Chinese: (i) borne by descendants of Chi Ren (遲任), a person who lived during the Shang dynasty (1600–1046  BC ). (ii) shortened form of the Chinese compound surname Yu-Chi (尉遲), originally the name of a tribe from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China. (iii) from the second element of the personal name Zi Chi (子遲), style name of Fan Xu, a student of Confucius (551–479  BC )."]}]},{"name":"Nicolo","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Rocco, Antonio, Carmine, Decio, Donato, Enrico, Mauro, Pasquale, Salvatore, Vincenzo.  Spanish Diego, Demetrio, Fernando, Palmira.","Italian (southern; <b>Nicolò</b>): variant of   Nicola  .","In some cases possibly also an American shortened (and altered) form of Greek patronymics   Nicolopoulos   or   Nikolopoulos  , or of composite names used as patronymics, such as <b>Nikologiannis</b> ‘John son of Nicholas’, or of Bulgarian and Macedonian patronymic   Nikolov  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Nicola","meanings":["Italian: from the male personal name <i>Nicola</i>, from Greek <i>Nikolaos</i> (see   Nicholas  ).","German (mainly Saarland) and French (Alsace and Lorraine): variant of   Nicolai   or   Nicolas  .","In some cases also an American shortened (and altered) form of Greek   Nikolas  , its variant   Nicolas  , or of any of various derivatives of the personal name <i>Nikola(o)s</i> ‘Nicholas’. Compare   Nicol  ."]}]},{"name":"Anna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[{"name":"Anne","meanings":["A name corrpted from Hannah, q.v. It is also found several times in a male name. From Ann, Anne, we have as nicknames Nan and Nancy"]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Anna Grimaldi di Nicolo was born about 1140, in Genova, Liguria, Italy as the daughter of Niccolo Grimaldi. She had at least 3 sons with Ansaldo II Doria. She died about 1190, in her hometown, at the age of 52."},"et":{"environ 1140–environ 1190":"umbes 1140–umbes 1190","1140–1190":"1140–1190","1140–1185":"1140–1185","1160–1190":"1160–1190","1165–1217":"1165–1217","1182–1220":"1182–1220","1115–1170":"1115–1170","1190":"1190","aproximadamente 1160":"umbes 1160","aproximadamente 1182":"umbes 1182","environ 1185":"umbes 1185","environ 1140":"umbes 1140","1165":"1165","1220":"1220","1185":"1185","environ 1170":"umbes 1170","1140":"1140","environ 1190":"umbes 1190","1182":"1182","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1217":"1217","1115":"1115","aproximadamente 1190":"umbes 1190","Genova, Liguria, Italie":"Genova, Liguria, Itaalia","Genova, Liguria, Italia":"Genova, Liguria, Itaalia"},"fi":{"environ 1140–environ 1190":"noin 1140–noin 1190","1140–1190":"1140–1190","1140–1185":"1140–1185","1160–1190":"1160–1190","1165–1217":"1165–1217","1182–1220":"1182–1220","1115–1170":"1115–1170","1190":"1190","aproximadamente 1160":"noin 1160","aproximadamente 1182":"noin 1182","environ 1185":"noin 1185","environ 1140":"noin 1140","1165":"1165","1220":"1220","1185":"1185","environ 1170":"noin 1170","1140":"1140","environ 1190":"noin 1190","1182":"1182","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1217":"1217","1115":"1115","aproximadamente 1190":"noin 1190","Genova, Liguria, Italie":"Genova, Liguria, Italia","Gen